      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Tennis Match</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Kurt Nielsen letter, commenting on September 2 editorial advocating elimination of pay disparities between male and female athletes at US Open, says it failed to mention another inequality, namely, that men are required to win three sets per match to advance or win, while women must win only two sets per match</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Equal Pay on the Tennis Court'' (editorial, Sept. 2):</p>
        <p>Your editorial doesn't mention that one glaring inequality still exists between male and female players at the United States Open: men are required to win three sets per match to advance or win, while women must win only two sets per match. Thus, men have to win 50 percent more sets than women for the same pay.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Equal Pay on the Tennis Court'' (editorial, Sept. 2):</p>
        <p>Your editorial doesn't mention that one glaring inequality still exists between male and female players at the United States Open: men are required to win three sets per match to advance or win, while women must win only two sets per match. Thus, men have to win 50 percent more sets than women for the same pay.</p>
        <p>If the United States Tennis Association wishes to fully eliminate pay disparities between the sexes, it must either reduce men's matches to the best-of-three sets or increase women's matches to the best-of-five sets.</p>
        <p>KURT NIELSEN  Closter, N.J., Sept. 2, 2000</p>
      </block>
